The paper discusses the use of machine learning for cognitive radio, specifically for spectrum sensing. This topic falls under the intersection of several computer science sub-disciplines, including information theory (cs.IT), machine learning (cs.LG), networking and internet architecture (cs.NI), systems and control (cs.SY), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Given the focus on machine learning and its application to cognitive radio, cs.IT and cs.LG are the most likely sub-categories. However, the paper also discusses the challenges of training data and domain adaptation, which suggests a focus on systems and control (cs.SY) and networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). Finally, the use of a generative adversarial network (GAN) for data augmentation and adaptation suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
